All languages consist of a set of specific patterns in terms of vocabulary, syntax and phonology that are adopted or accepted by its speakers. Native speakers naturally develop an understanding of these concepts from the environment around them as their language develops. Second language learners can implicitly gain knowledge about the language they are learning, but are also generally taught explicitly through classroom instruction as well. These differences in learning can affect the way a person is able to use the language at a later stage of acquisition. All language learners begin building a vocabulary or set of words in the language that can be used to convey meaning. %Language users create utterances with their vocabulary according to the accepted rules of the language. Languages have grammars which are language specific. These grammars inform users on how to use the language for things such as expressing past, present and future or what order to put words so that utterances are acceptable by native speakers. A clear example is phrase word order that differs with adjective placement between English and Spanish. In Spanish, \emph{una bolsa azul} 'a bag blue' when translated word by word; however, a better translation of the phrase would be 'a blue bag'. This difference arises between the two languages because Spanish prescribes the adjective to follow the noun it describes while English prescribes that adjective precede the noun. Words, like language word order, also possess a specific structures. 
The main focus of this chapter is what underlies the word structure used to create these words in a given language. 
%While the discussions below the word-level can include units such as phonemes and moras, this study focuses on the syllabic structure of words \parencite{Cutler1994-qg,Cutler2002-ty,Kim2008-qc,Labrune2012-lh,Nazzi1998-zc,Otake1993-kd,Pierrehumbert1995-jr,Tranel1991-oa}.
The discussion revolves around syllables because permissible syllable structures differ between English and Spanish. These differences in syllable structure have potential side effects for the L1 Spanish and L1 English speakers when performing tasks such as word segmentation or accessing their mental lexicons when processing Spanish. Therefore, this chapter sought to understand and document differences in syllabic intuition through the use of a two-alternate forced choice task where participants had to choose between two options for the word-initial syllable of Spanish words.

In order to understand why differences may exist, a look at sub-syllabic units is necessary. Syllables can be further broken down systematically into its individual phonemes, or individual sound segments. It is important to define a few crucial terms before the current discussion on syllable structure and its effect on other language processes. The internal structure of a syllable is made up of phonemes which combine to form the onset, nucleus and coda of syllables. The onset of the syllable is a consonant or a consonant cluster that occurs before the nucleus and the coda is a consonant or a consonant cluster occurring after the nucleus. The nucleus is the center and most sonorant portion of the syllable, which is typically realized as a vowel. The rime of a syllable is simply the combination of the nucleus and coda. However, acceptable syllable structures or the phoneme combinations that can form a syllable's sub-units are not language specific. For instance, what phonemes and the max allowable number of phonemes that can combine to create onsets, nuclei and codas differ between languages. Where these differences occur are areas where it might be expected to see learner difficulties. Syllable formations becomes a crucial factor to this because the L1 background of the control group is Spanish while the target group is English. This will have implications for where each group will divide words into individual syllables. Therefore, this experiment is gaining an understanding of the control group's native syllable intuition and comparing it to the second language syllable intuitions of the target group. 

Now, the discussion turns to the acquisition processes of these linguistic units because they are directly related to L1 and L2 backgrounds of the participants. While this study incorporates L1 speaker controls, the main goal of this study is how second language learners of Spanish process their L2. The first major difference in native speakers and second language learners is the state of the language faculty at the onset of acquisition. For a native speaker, the infant is essentially starting with a blank template. In fact, infants generally go from having the ability to discriminate between ambiguous sounds whether or not they are related to their native language needs during the first year of life. Over the course of the first year they begin to narrow down their perceptual range of sound discriminatory abilities \parencite{Bosch2003-jm,Byers-Heinlein2010-fv,Shafer2011-mv,Sundara2008-tc}. This perceptual narrowing suggests that infants begin to ignore sound discriminations that are not useful to processing their native language and paying more attention to those sound discriminations that do make a difference. %The literature on infants are using sound discriminations to show how these eventually become part of the phonemic inventory of the language. What constitutes a phoneme in a given language is determined by two sound segments being in contrastive distribution, which occurs when two segments occur in the same phonological context and spur a change in meaning. A minimal pair test is commonly used to support the existence of two separate phonemes in a language. The minimal pair test utilizes two words with different meanings and exactly one phoneme difference between the two. For example, /b\ae t/ 'bat' and /b\ae g/ 'bag' share phonemes in the onset and nucleus, but the singleton coda phoneme differs. Given that the single phonemic difference in the coda position changes the meaning of the word, it can be argued that /t/ and /g/ are two distinct phonemes of English. 
All infants learning their native language will eventually distinguish between sounds according to phonemic inventories of the language they are acquiring. They will also learn how to combine these phonemes into acceptable syllable and words that conform to the phonotactic properties of their L1. %It is important to note that not all phonemes exist in all languages and even when two languages do contain the same phonemes, the properties of those phonemes can have different phonetic properties. To illustrate this point, the phonemes /p/ and /b/ will be exemplified in Arabic, English and Spanish. English and Spanish infants would encounter processing issues if they lost the distinction between these two phonemes because they are contrastive in the language, but an infant learning Arabic would not be faced with the same disadvantage because these two phonemes are not contrastive. The minimal pair test with \emph{pig} and \emph{big} in English or \emph{bala} 'bullet' and \emph{pala} 'shovel' in Spanish, differ only in the distinction between phonemes /p/ and /b/ in the word-initial onset positions. This supports the claim that /p/ and /b/ are distinct phonemes because they are in contrastive distribution in both English and Spanish. However, minimal pairs for /p/ and /b/ cannot be found in Arabic due to the fact the /p/ is not a sound found the phonemic inventory. As a result, it makes no difference to the Arabic learning infant if they discriminate between the two sounds. To sum up, it is important for English and Spanish infants to develop two separate phonological categories for /p/ and /b/ to process their L1 language, while retaining these two separate categories for Arabic infants would provide no processing advantage.
On the other hand, second language learners do not have a clean slate to build their target language on. This adds another layer of complexity to the task of acquiring second language phonological system because their L2 phonology will be filtered through their L1 phonological system. In this case, the second language learner already has their L1 language system in place, complete with its vocabulary, syntax, phonology and all the nuances that accompany these systems. %In terms of phonolgical categories, this results in two possible outcomes. In the case of the Arabic native speaker, they are confronted with a sound distinction they learned to ignore when they attempt to learn English or Spanish. This problem surfaces in both perception and production as they cannot hear the difference between /p/ and /b/ nor can they produce these sounds accurately. This is a case where the L1 Arabic speaker needs to learn a new phonemic distinction and create a new phonological category for their L2 that is absent from their L1 phonology system. %\ttodo[inline]{reference} 
