A common example that illustrates this is L1 Spanish speaker's pronunciation of the English word \emph{Spain} as a two syllable word, /\textschwa s.peIn/, in order to align with Spanish phonotactics. Likewise, L1 English speakers do not recognize that onsets are more restrictive in Spanish and produce L2 Spanish words according to their L1 English phonology. L2 Spanish speakers will often produce \emph{in.struc.tor} rather than the native accepted pronunciation of \emph{ins.truc.tor} because a complex onset of /str/ is acceptable in their L1 English. Another relevant example for the L1 English-L2 Spanish speaker is the intervocalic consonants /r/ and /l/. The Spanish word \emph{para} can be syllabified by L1 English speakers as \emph{par.ra} or \emph{pa.ra}. This later example is due to ambisyllabicity, which allows for a single phoneme to be present in the coda of the first syllable and the onset of the second syllable. Ambisyllabicity effectively blurs the syllable boundary and is found in English, but not in Spanish. Therefore, when L1 English speakers transfer these phonological properties to their L2 Spanish, they create syllable boundaries that differ from Spanish native-like norms. These difference can and need to be investigated so that there is better understanding about how they may affect experimental designs and other language processes such as word segmentation or lexical access. As a result, the current study utilizes a two-alternative forced choice task to gather the syllabic intuitions of L1 Spanish and L1 English speakers. It is expected that L1 English speakers will have less consistent syllabic intuitions patterns in Spanish than the L1 Spanish speakers. If Spanish syllabic intuitions differ between the L1 Spanish and L1 English speakers it may predict differences in word segmentation strategies that are tested in Chapters \ref{ch-seg-lab} and \ref{ch-seg-online}.

