%\subsection{Spanish and English Syllable Structure}
There are many similarities and differences in syllable properties between Spanish and English. In terms of vowel reduction, English readily allows vowel reduction to a schwa in unstressed syllables while Spanish does not allow for vowel reduction at all. While Spanish has very clear syllable boundaries, English allows for ambisyllabicity where one phoneme is shared between two adjacent syllables. Internal to the syllable structure, the phonemes that can combine to form the onset differ between the two languages as well. According to \textcite{Harris1983-vu} onsets can only have up to two segments and the consonants that can fill onset slots are highly restricted in Spanish. In a complex onset, the first segment must be an obstruent and the second segment can only be a liquid while any consonant will suffice in a single segment onset. However, English permits up to three segments in the onset position as shown by words such as \emph{street} and \emph{spring}. Similar differences in complexity are found in English and Spanish codas. English codas frequently contain two phonemes with the possibility of four phonemes in words such as [sIks\texttheta s] 'sixths'. On the other hand, complex codas are not common at all in Spanish \parencite{Whitley1986-nc}. When complex codas do occur in Spanish, the second phoneme is an /s/ as in the word \emph{ins-ti-tu-to} 'institute'. \textcite{Harris1983-vu} claims that Spanish syllables can have maximally five segments as in the first syllable of \emph{claustro} [kláws-tro] 'cloister'. This maximal five segment syllable length is a shorter than can be found in English words such as \emph{strengths} [st\textturnr \textepsilon \textipa{N}k\texttheta s], which contains eight segments. These differences in syllable properties will likely affect how L1 English and L1 Spanish speakers process syllables and words when segmenting speech in the two languages.
%\ttodo[inline]{This section needs to focus on ambisyllabicity from a phonology-based perspective. No experimental data needed in this section.}

From a phonology-based perspective, these abstract concepts of phonemes and syllables structures---onsets, nuclei, codas, rimes---had been created by linguists in order to explain language grammars and phonological processes that can been seen in everyday language use. %Since phonemes combine to build syllables, the focus of the current study, it would be expected that these difficulties could extend to syllable structures as well. 
In instances where L1 and L2 phonological systems differ is where the evidence of this transfer becomes very salient in phonetics. For example, legal combinations of phonemes in the onset of the L1 may be illegal combinations in the L2 or vice versa. Using the onset position of English and Spanish syllables, it is possible to see why certain combinations cause L2 learners trouble. While English allows onsets such as /sp(r), st(r), sk, sl/, Spanish does not allow these combinations of phonemes in the onset position. %\ttodo[inline]{is this list exhaustive? Check out phonology notes from Colina} 
Spanish speakers attempt to overcome this obstacle in their L2 English by inserting an epenthetic /\textschwa/ to pull the /s/ into the coda position of the first syllable and the remaining consonants remain in the onset of the second syllable. This breaks up the illegal consonant cluster and the English word now conforms to the constraints of their L1 Spanish phonology. A common example that illustrates this is the English word \emph{Spain}. Since /sp/ is an illegal onset in Spanish, an L1 Spanish speaker will commonly produce a two syllable word, /\textschwa s.peIn/, in order to align with Spanish phonotactics. Likewise, English speakers do not recognize that these complex onsets are illegal in Spanish and produce words according to their L1 English phonology creating syllable boundaries that differ from Spanish native-like norms. L2 Spanish speakers will often produce \emph{in.struc.tor} rather than the native Spanish accepted pronunciation of \emph{ins.truc.tor} because an onset of /str/ is acceptable in their L1 English. 

A second major difference between English and Spanish is ambisyllabicity.%, which refers to a single phoneme being part of two separate syllables in the word. 
To place this into context, \emph{balada} 'ballad' and \emph{baldosa} 'tile' will be used illustrate how ambisyllabicity functions. Ambisyllabicity is not present in Spanish; therefore, L1 Spanish speakers would converge on only one syllabification pattern---\emph{ba.la.da} and \emph{bal.do.sa}. In contrast to very clear Spanish syllable boundaries, English allows for ambisyllabicity, which blur English syllable boundary in certain phonological environments. As a result, ambisyllabicity creates an environment where multiple syllabification options exist for the L1 English speakers in their L2 Spanish. One pattern is syllabifying in the same manner as the L1 Spanish group for both \emph{ba.la.da} and \emph{bal.do.sa}. The second candidate that exists for L1 English speakers causes the intervocalic /l/ to be brought into the coda position for the word initial syllable while it remains in the onset position of the second syllable \emph{bal.la.da}. This effect can be seen in English syllabifications such as \emph{bal.ance} and \emph{bal.lance} for the word \emph{balance}. In the case of \emph{bal.do.sa}, no divergence from the Spanish-like syllabification pattern is expected because /ld/ is not a legal onset in English. Therefore, this is also a very clear syllable for both L1 Spanish and L1 English speakers. These intervocalic liquids, /r/ and /l/, are prime candidates for L1 English to L2 Spanish transfer of ambisyllabicity.

