\subsection{Experimental Evidence for Syllable Intuitions}
%\ttodo[inline]{You discuss the studies one by one, making no connections across them, just listing, providing tons of details on method. All these studies are on English. Need less information on the Treiman studies, need to make connections, and currently missing the a large component on Spanish syllable structure.}

There is a large amount of research that aimed to gain a better understanding of syllabic intuitions. \textcite{MacKay1972-ii} studied the structure of words and syllables. They analyzed speech errors where people produced an incorrect word stemming from the combination of two real words that have similar meanings. This type of analysis looked at the reasons why a combination of \emph{behavior} and \emph{deportment}, both related to a person's behavior or manners, produced a speech error \emph{behortment}. \textcite{MacKay1972-ii} analyzed synonymic intrusions in German and English resulting in support for the fact that syllables minimally consist of three subunits. They argued that syllables contained individual phonemes, consonant clusters and a sub-syllabic unit that combines a vowel and final consonants. Their sub-syllabic unit is otherwise known as the rime in later literature. Given evidence from both German and English, they argued that this may be a language universal principle. A second common task utilized in this previous research is picture naming \parencite{Ferrand1996-vu,Keffala2018-ta,Olson2013-dy,Schiller1998-ph}. A picture naming task shows the participant a picture and asks them to name what they see in the picture they were shown. This is a way of eliciting words without having the influence of outside phonology or orthography intervene in the production of lexical items. Picture naming allows researcher to collect a large amount of data quickly because researchers have control over their experimental items and designs, which can even include nonwords. These are distinct advantages over the synonymic intrusions which have to be filtered out from large corpora of spoken data containing a lot of noise or unusable data. However, synonymic intrusion does provide natural language data which does mimic the real language use found in day to day environments. While both of these tasks were beneficial to investigating syllable structures, they require a large working vocabulary to analyze real word data. Several other tasks such as phoneme substitution, syllable blending and syllable repetition have been developed to study the internal structure of syllables using experimental methods. These experimental-based studies require less dependency on large working vocabularies and can even utilize nonwords to test syllabic intuitions of a speaker. These are viable options for the current study because its main goal is to understand the syllabic intuitions for L1 Spanish and L1 English speakers have and how they may differ from one another. These syllabic intuitions may have further implications for other phonological processes such as a person's ability to segment words or access the mental lexicon. Much of the previous research stemmed from English studies by Treiman. \textcite{Treiman1983-jr} used experimental methods that attempted to validate the psychological reality of the internal structure of syllables that had been proposed by theoretical phonology. French, like Spanish, is another romance language that does not allow ambisyllabicity. As a result, French and Spanish contrast English in a similar manner. Since Spanish syllabic intuitions have not been studied through experimental means, several French studies also become very relevant to the current discussion.

In a large study, \textcite{Treiman1983-jr} conducted seven different tests involving novel word games. The outcomes of these word games provided strong support for the existence of the onset and rime as internal components of the syllable. 
