In addition to the tasks that focused solely on onsets as a psychological reality, \textcite{Treiman1983-jr} used a syllable blending to test for the preference of splitting syllables into smaller proposed constituent parts such as the coda and rime. In this syllable game, participants had to learn four different rules that used monosyllabic CCVCC syllables---where C represents a consonant and V represents a vowel. %As before, the syllable blending involved combining two syllables to make a new monosyllabic syllable. The syllables /flirz/ and /gruns/ are used to illustrate each of the four games, which were administered to the same participants on four separate visits. In the first game, C-CVCC, the correct response would have been /fruns/, which split the onset of both syllables keeping only the first phoneme of syllable one and the final four phonemes of syllable two. The second game, CC-VCC, resulted in /fluns/, which combined the complete onset of the first syllable and the complete rime of the second syllable. The first two games allowed for a comparison of rules where one forced participants to split the onset consonant cluster and the other forced them to keep it intact. The third games, CCV-CC, resulted in /flins/ by taking the onset and vowel of the first syllable and the coda of second syllable. The final game, CCVC-C, resulted in /flirs/ by splitting the coda in both syllables to combine the first four phonemes of syllable one and the last phoneme of syllable two. Game three allowed researchers to compare preferences to keep the coda together as a cohesive unit with game four, which forced participants to split the coda consonant cluster. 
Participants chose to split and blend the syllables between the onset and rime and did so with less errors, % than the other three games. 
which garnered further support for the onset as cohesive unit. Interestingly though, the same support was not found for the coda as a cohesive unit. \textcite{Treiman1983-jr} found no preference for splitting between the vowel and coda, V.CC, or splitting the coda consonant cluster, VC.C. In short, the findings suggest that the logical sub-syllabic units making up syllables were the onset and the rime as they did not find consistent support for vowel and the coda division within the structure of the rime. %\textcite{Treiman1983-jr} then tested the same concept in the coda position. They trained participants with four examples again following this rule when adding the syllable /vi/ to the syllable /fug/ becomes /vig-fu/. The testing phase then included stimuli such as /w\textopeno st/ which could be repeated as /vist-w\textopeno/ in support of coda reality or as /vit-w\textopeno s/ in support of splitting the consonant cluster. Again, participants showed they responded based on phonology and preferred to keep the coda consonant cluster intact. 
