The first CCV game aligned the phoneme substitution with the complete onset and the rime being unchanged even though the coda position was empty. The second game for CCV syllables forced participants to substitute phonemes that split the onset consonant cluster. The results of the four games gave additional support for the cohesiveness of the onset and rime as logical subsyllabic units. Additional support for this claim also came from \textcite{Treiman1988-kt} who showed the nucleus of an English syllable is more closely associated to the phoneme that comes it after it---coda consonants---than the phonemes before it---onset consonants. Participants rated syllables as less acceptable when the syllable was not divided between the onset and coda and preferred blending syllables where the nucleus and coda remained intact. 

