The current experiment set out to gain an understanding of how well participants can accurately syllabify syllables of Spanish. The syllable intuition experiment is an important step in the process because how a person syllabifies words should have a direct effect on other languages processes that rely on the syllable in some way. Potential examples include how fast a participant can retrieve a lexical item from their mental lexicon or how useful the syllable is in their language segmentation abilities. The current dissertation is focused on the latter of the two processes---word segmentation. It is expected that syllabic intuitions will vary based on being a L1 speaker of Spanish or a L1 speaker of English even though all participants were bilingual Spanish--English speakers. These expected differences in syllabification patterns are likely to stem from L1 background or language dominance, which match in the current project due to predetermined recruitment and inclusion criteria. This experiment begins to build a database of Spanish–English bilinguals syllabification patterns of Spanish words, which could help to determine whether or not language dominance is the source of different syllabification patterns. The main question is interested in whether or not L1 Spanish speakers have differing syllabic intuitions for Spanish syllables than L1 English speakers.

%The main question this chapter seeks to answer is whether or not speakers segment words differently. If they do, how do they differ between groups of speakers and/or syllable structure type---CV or CVC.

In order to collect intuitions on syllables of Spanish, participants were given a two-alternative forced choice task that was a modified version of the data collection task used by \textcite{Treiman1990-fw}. In the current study, the two-alternative forced choice task was only concerned with the word-initial syllable structure rather than the complete syllabification of the word. During the syllable intuition experiment, participants were visually shown a word on the screen, which was replaced by letter sequences of two or three letters. The letter sequences represented the CV or CVC initial syllable options for the word that had just been presented. %\todo{removed because not all participants in this chapter were tested on segmentation strategies. some were tested on lexical access which is not reported on in this dissertation}This is the first study to my knowledge that has elicited syllabification patterns of experimental items used in a visual letter sequence monitoring task in order to connect syllabification of items to segmentation results with the same participants. This is not an important point either because it does not matter whether the words were identical, only that the type of words were similar.
As with all experimental designs, running the experiment came with some assumptions in order to interpret the results. It accepts the fact that only CV and CVC syllable types were used in experimental items although this is only a subset of valid syllable structures in Spanish. An important distinction to make is the difference between implicit and explicit knowledge. Chapters \ref{ch-seg-lab} and \ref{ch-seg-online} conduct visual word segmentation experiments where implicit phonological awareness is tested because participants were never told that they were monitoring for syllables. However, the current chapter on syllabic intuitions is testing explicit phonological awareness because participants are being asked to choose the first syllable of the word. In other words, participants in this chapter knew that they were identifying syllables and not some other linguistic unit.
 

