Due to the fact that the L1 backgrounds differ between groups of participants in the current study, several predictions can be made. Since the experiment is conducted in Spanish, it is expected that the L1 Spanish group will have a high degree of consistency in their syllabic intuitions causing them to perform at or near the accuracy ceiling. The L1 English group is expected to perform less consistently or accurately when compared to the L1 Spanish group. The main reason for this prediction is that L1 English speakers could transfer their phonological knowledge of ambisyllabicity to the L2 Spanish. A difference in syllabic intuitions would result in lower accuracy rates because of words such as \emph{paloma}. L1 Spanish speakers will only have one syllabification pattern---\emph{pa.lo.ma} or word-initial CV structure. L1 English speakers will have two potential syllabification patterns---\emph{pa.lo.ma} and \emph{pal.lo.ma}. L1 English speakers choosing the second option would be indicating that the word-initial syllable structure was CVC rather than the CV L1 Spanish speakers should be in agreement with. Words that create environments where ambisyllabicity can occur will be responsible for lower accuracy rates because other words such as \emph{palmera} will be syllabified in the same manner by both groups. L1 English speakers will not syllabify as \emph{pal.lme.ra} because /lm/ is an illegal onset in English just as it is in Spanish. Therefore, both groups should consistently syllabify as \emph{pal.me.ra}, which indicates a CVC word-initial syllable structure choice. Similar predictions would be made for the intervocalic /r/ in Spanish word pairing \emph{joroba--jornada}. These intervocalic liquids, /r/ and /l/, are prime candidates for ambisyllabicity to appear in English. This should cause differences in syllabification patterns of the Spanish stimuli, but only within the L1 English group.

