\subsection{Participants}
\label{sub-intuition-part}
All participants reported in this chapter were recruited for experiments that took place in an in-person laboratory setting. Two groups of participants took part in the syllabic intuition experiment. L1 Spanish speakers who were second language learners of English served as the control group. L1 English speakers who were second language learners of Spanish were used for the target group. All recruited participants resided in their L1 environment, or birth country, at the time of data collection. 

Due to the methods used in data collection several pre-analysis steps were conducted to ensure that participants actually represented the intended group for which they were recruited. The participants were placed into their appropriate group based off of the additional data collected through the LexTALE, LexTALE-Esp and the Bilingual Language Profile (BLP) tasks that were completed during the same visit as syllabic intuition task. The BLP, the LexTALE and the LexTALE-Esp vocabulary tests are described in full detail in Chapter \ref{ch-sampling} Section \ref{sec-instruments}. Since these tasks were completed during a single experimental session, it was not always possible to determine whether or not all participants were representative of the group until after all information had been collected and additional linguistic measures and language background had been thoroughly reviewed. Figure \ref{plt-intuition-eng-vocab} shows the distribution of vocabulary scores for English in terms of percent correct responses to the LexTALE task while Figure \ref{plt-intuition-izura-vocab} shows the vocabulary scores for Spanish calculated by the method given in \textcite{Izura2014-yw}---referred to as the Izura score throughout the remainder of this dissertation. The percentage score was also calculated for the percent correct responses to LexTALE-Esp items in order to calculate the difference between L1 and L2 vocabulary sizes. Participants analyzed in this chapter were those who had a larger L1 vocabulary relative to their L2 vocabulary size. These participants were removed because having a larger L2 vocabulary is an indicator of a stronger language dominance in their second language than their L1. Figure \ref{plt-intuition-vocab-diff} shows the difference between English and Spanish vocabulary sizes and Figure \ref{plt-intuition-lang-dom} shows the language dominance score calculated from the BLP. Both of these figures show two clearly distinct groups of participants that align 