%\ttodo[inline]{This interpretation is framed in terms of Correct/Incorrect. Linguists have framed these syllabification patterns to be correct: ba.la.da CV and bal.cón CVC or incorrect: ba.la.da CVC and bal.cón CV. Explicitly state that ba.la.da as CV and bal.cón as CVC are defined as correct (1) and any other answer as incorrect (0) in the current study to give readers a definition as to how to interpret these results. In the definition of these terms it may help to put them in double quotes: "correct", "incorrect" and "accuracy".}

In this analysis, there are a few terms that need to be defined in order to interpret the results below. The term "correct" has been attributed to CV responses for words like \emph{ba.la.da} and \emph{ca.mi.sa} while a CVC response to these items were counted as "incorrect". Similarly, CVC responses were scored as correct for \emph{bal.do.sa} and \emph{cam.pa.na} while a CV response was considered incorrect. Correct scores were given a value of 1 and incorrect responses were given a value of 0. The term "accuracy" in this chapter refers to the proportion of correct responses. In the first step of the analysis, the accuracy score was calculated for each participant as the proportion of correct responses. Each participant received two individual scores, one average for CV syllables and a second for the average of CVC syllables. The accuracy data then underwent a logit transformation. The untransformed accuracy scores have been used in the descriptive statistics while the logit transformed scores were utilized for inferential statistics. The dataset contained raw proportion correct and logit transformed correct response rates for both L1 Spanish speakers and L1 English speakers. The data structure contained a between-subjects factor of \emph{Group} with two levels---L1 Spanish and L1 English speakers. The dataset also contained a second factor, \emph{Structure}, that was within-subjects and also included two levels---CV and CVC syllable structure. The complete dataset consisted of 
