\section{Discussion}
%\ttodo[inline]{Discussion. We need a proper discussion, at least three times longer. The Discussion needs to summarize the findings in plain English, then discuss them one by one in the context of the literature you discussed in the Background section, then discuss them in the context of your research question and your predictions. Were your predictions correct? Why not. You may explain what are some possible limitations of the study, but this is rather secondary. The current version of the Discussion focuses exclusively on secondary issues.}

This chapter reported on the \Sexpr{nrow(intuition_desc)} bilingual Spanish--English participants who completed a Spanish syllabification experiment. Crucially, the experiment ran in this chapter investigated whether or not the two groups agreed on the syllabic structures of Spanish they were segmenting as a result of L1 background. The results indicated that the two groups differed in their abilities to correctly syllabify Spanish syllables when compared to the standard Spanish syllabification patterns set forth by theoretical phonology. The L1 Spanish speakers performed much closer to the prescribed syllabification patterns than the L1 English speakers. While this result may seem obvious on the surface, the effects it may have on other language processing skills is likely to be substantial. Since this difference was found when asking the participants to identify the first syllable of the word, it is possible that differences could also be found in lexical access. Previous lexical access research that has been done suggested the word initial syllable may be a key to accessing the mental lexicon \parencite{Cooper2002-rx,Cutler1988-kg,Tabossi2000-xn,Tagliapietra2009-uc}. It may also affect word segmentation abilities in that the breaking down of words into syllables could be different. For a full discussion on Spanish word segmentation, see Chapters \ref{ch-seg-lab} and \ref{ch-seg-online} of this dissertation. Chapter \ref{ch-seg-lab} reports on the same participants discussed in the current chapter who completed the in-person visual segmentation experiment less the participants who completed the lexical access experiment, which was not reported in this project due to insufficient data collection at the time that COVID-19 broke out.

The discussion now returns the main research question on whether or not Spanish syllabic intuitions differ between L1 Spanish speakers and L1 English speakers. Indeed, the results showed that these groups differed from one another. As predicted, the L1 Spanish group had a higher accuracy rate, or within group consensus, than the L1 English group for both syllable types. These results point to differences in L1 background or language dominance. In the current study, all participants had a language dominance that aligned with their L1 background. Therefore, it was not possible to determine whether L1 background or language dominance was responsible for the differences in syllabic intuitions between the two groups. In order to differentiate these two factors, a study would need to be designed that investigated speaker groups that had a language dominance that aligned with their L2 rather than their L1. For example, L1 Spanish speakers who had immigrated to an English speaking region and had become more dominant in the L2 English would be an ideal candidate. Likewise, an L1 English speaker who had immigrated to Spanish speaking region and become more dominant in their L2 Spanish would also be ideal candidate. While this study recruited people for in-person experiments, a syllabic intuition study using a visual presentation method could easily be conducted online. With many online participant pools such as Amazon Mechanical Turk and Prolific, online studies have become much easier to conduct and allow researchers access to more specific and targeted populations that would otherwise be unreachable.

The results clearly establish a difference in syllabic intuitions between L1 Spanish and L1 English speaking groups. Overall, there were less accurate responses to CV syllables than CVC syllables when looking at the pooled data from both groups. This finding was in line with the hypothesis that the CV stimuli in this study would be susceptible to ambisyllabicity. A reduction in the consensus of the syllabification of CV syllables should have been found if the L1 English group transferred there knowledge of ambisyllabicity to their L2 Spanish. Since Spanish does not permit ambisyllabicity, L1 English speakers will diverge from the standard Spanish syllabification patterns in word such as \emph{balada}, but not in words such as \emph{baldosa}. Thus, where the intervocalic liquid has the option to pulled into the coda position of the word-initial syllable, some L1 English speakers will identify the first syllable of \emph{balada} as a closed CVC syllable rather than open CV syllable following standard Spanish syllabification. Given that the evidence is only found in the CV syllable type, ambisyllabicity is the likely cause of the reduction in consistent syllabification patterns because words such as \emph{baldosa} would not be a phonological environment for ambisyllabicity in English either. While the effect did not remain significant within either group of speakers, the raw percentages still suggested that CV syllables were less consistent than CVC syllables, but only for the L1 English group. The raw percentage scores actually showed a significant difference for the L1 English group, but the effect did not hold after the logit transformation. This difference was in the expected direction with CV syllables being responded to with much less accuracy than CVC syllables for the L1 English group. Neither the raw percentage scores nor the logit transformed accuracy rates differed between CV and CVC syllable types for the L1 Spanish group. Even though the current study cannot make a definitive claim about the L1 English transference of ambisyllabicity to their L2 Spanish syllable intuitions, there definitely appeared to be something happening to their CV syllabification patterns. 

One limitation in this study is that it only reports on error rates. While reaction times were collected during the course of this experiment, they were not reliable due to experimental design constraints. The design of the experiment displayed the word for 1500 milliseconds before the answer choices were visible to participants and responses were not accepted until the 1500 milliseconds had passed. Most participants began to answer very quickly once they realized that the answer choices, CV or CVC, were not changing. In other words a participant always used the same response button to indicate a CV syllable and the same response button to indicate a CVC syllable throughout the entire experiment. Many participants began anticipating the answer screen to appear so they could respond. This made it impossible to detect stuck keys from a person inadvertently holding the button or excluding responses based on previously reported response time cutoffs, i.e. 100 or 200 milliseconds. A future study could take advantage of reaction as an independent variable of interest by allowing participants to respond as soon as they had made their decision rather than forcing them to wait. It would also be possible to switch answer response buttons, although this may unnecessarily complicate the task and served as the reason for not doing so in the current study. Nonetheless, utilizing reaction time data with syllabification experiments may make predictions possible in tasks for other language processing tasks where segmentation, lexical access or vocabulary size is concerned. Visual and auditory monitoring, word-naming and lexical decision experiments could be much more informative with syllabic intuitions guiding experimental item selection. The last possible limitation was the two-alternative forced choice task of CV and CVC. Future studies may benefit by increasing the number of syllable types. Including other syllable types such as CCV, VC or VCC in the list would increase the complexity of the task, but would resemble more real-life language processing tasks encountered by language learners.

